	introduction  
	------------
barbar is a minimal status bar aggregator using shared memory for IPC
it reads status updates from user modules and displays them as a combined string
it is WM and OS agnostic, and simply prints out the string to stdout
tested on Unix (OpenBSD, MacOS, and Linux)

	usage  
	-----
start the aggregator:  
    barbar  
run individual modules to update status:  
    bartime  
    dailies  
    pomodoro  

dailies can be used with flags to log study time:  
    dailies -t 30 -p 15
this adds 30 minutes to theory and 15 minutes to practice

pomodoro can be used with flags to customise study time:
    pomodoro -t 13 -l 3 -s 2 -f 4 -n 8 
this starts 8 pomodoros of 13 minutes with 3 minute long breaks 
at a 4 cycle interval, and 2 minute short breaks otherwise

the order, number, and names of modules can be set in config.h

	make commands  
	-------------
    make           build all modules
    make install   copy all binaries to $HOME/.local/bin
    make clean     remove built binaries
    make uninstall remove installed binaries from $HOME/.local/bin

	notes 
	-----
    ensure barbar is running first to aggregate and display status updates
    look at config.h for barbar (aggregator) config, e.g. refresh rate
    look at modules/config_MODULE.h for module config, e.g. the date formatting
